To test BlockDeviceMapping, use a snippet like:
{code}
        "BlockDeviceMappings":[ { "DeviceName":"/dev/sdc", "Ebs":{ "VolumeSize":"5", "DeleteOnTermination":"true"} } ]
{code}
Make sure if the instance is instance-store, the stack fails (ebs block device mappings require a bfebs instance), and that if the instance is ebs, changing deleteOnTermination only will leave the instance with the same id, but changing anything else will require replacement.

To test DisableApiTermination, add a snippet like
{code}
"DisableApiTermination" : "true"
{code}
and try to terminate the instance, or try euca-describe-instance-attribute --disable-api-termination <instance>
Non-existant value in template should make the value "false", and this should not require replacement.

IamInstanceProfile
{code}
{
  "Parameters" : {
    "ImageId" : {"Type":"String"},
    "KeyName" : {"Type":"String"}
  },
  "Resources" : {
    "Ec2Instance":{
      "Type":"AWS::EC2::Instance",
      "Properties":{
        "ImageId":{ "Ref":"ImageId" },
        "KeyName":{ "Ref":"KeyName" },
        "IamInstanceProfile" : {"Ref" : "IP1"}
      }
    },
    "Role1":{
      "Type":"AWS::IAM::Role",
      "Properties":{
        "AssumeRolePolicyDocument":{
          "Version":"2012-10-17",
          "Statement":[
            {
              "Effect":"Allow",
              "Principal":{
                "Service":[
                  "ec2.amazonaws.com"
                ]
              },
              "Action":[
                "sts:AssumeRole"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "Path":"/",
        "Policies":[
          {
            "PolicyName":"root",
            "PolicyDocument":{
              "Version":"2012-10-17",
              "Statement":[
                {
                  "Effect":"Allow",
                  "Action":"*",
                  "Resource":"*"
                }
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    "IP1":{
      "Type":"AWS::IAM::InstanceProfile",
      "Properties":{
        "Path":"/",
        "Roles":[
          {
            "Ref":"Role1"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    "Role2":{
      "Type":"AWS::IAM::Role",
      "Properties":{
        "AssumeRolePolicyDocument":{
          "Version":"2012-10-17",
          "Statement":[
            {
              "Effect":"Allow",
              "Principal":{
                "Service":[
                  "ec2.amazonaws.com"
                ]
              },
              "Action":[
                "sts:AssumeRole"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        "Path":"/",
        "Policies":[
          {
            "PolicyName":"root",
            "PolicyDocument":{
              "Version":"2012-10-17",
              "Statement":[
                {
                  "Effect":"Allow",
                  "Action":"*",
                  "Resource":"*"
                }
              ]
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    "IP2":{
      "Type":"AWS::IAM::InstanceProfile",
      "Properties":{
        "Path":"/",
        "Roles":[
          {
            "Ref":"Role2"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }
}
{code}
Create the above stack, then change the IamInstanceProfile in the instance to point to the other profile.  In any case, a replacement instance will be created.

To test NetworkInterface, consider the following template
{code}
{
  "Parameters" : {
    "KeyName" : {
      "Type" : "String"
    },
    "ImageId" : {
      "Type" : "String"
    }
  },
  "Resources" : {
    "VPC" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::VPC",
      "Properties" : {
        "CidrBlock" : "10.0.0.0/16",
        "Tags" : [ {"Key" : "Application", "Value" : { "Ref" : "AWS::StackId"} } ]
      }
    },
    "InternetGateway" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::InternetGateway",
      "Properties" : {
        "Tags" : [ {"Key" : "Application", "Value" : { "Ref" : "AWS::StackId"} } ]
      }
    },
    "Subnet" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Subnet",
      "Properties" : {
        "VpcId" : { "Ref" : "VPC" },
        "CidrBlock" : "10.0.0.0/24",
        "Tags" : [ {"Key" : "Application", "Value" : { "Ref" : "AWS::StackId"} } ]
      }
    },

    "AttachGateway" : {
       "Type" : "AWS::EC2::VPCGatewayAttachment",
       "Properties" : {
         "VpcId" : { "Ref" : "VPC" },
         "InternetGatewayId" : { "Ref" : "InternetGateway" }
       }
    },
    "SecurityGroup":{
      "Type":"AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup",
      "Properties":{
        "GroupDescription":"Cloudformation VPC Group",
        "VpcId": {"Ref":"VPC"},
        "SecurityGroupEgress" : [ {"IpProtocol": "udp", "FromPort": "0", "ToPort": "128", "CidrIp":"0.0.0.0/0"}],
        "SecurityGroupIngress": [ {"IpProtocol":"tcp", "FromPort":"22", "ToPort":"22", "CidrIp":"0.0.0.0/0"}],
        "Tags" : [ {"Key" : "Application", "Value" : { "Ref" : "AWS::StackId"} } ]
      }
    },

    "Ec2Instance":{
      "Type":"AWS::EC2::Instance",
      "Properties":{
        "ImageId": {"Ref":"ImageId"},
        "KeyName" : {"Ref":"KeyName"},
        "NetworkInterfaces" : [{"DeviceIndex" : "0", "GroupSet": [{"Ref":"SecurityGroup"}], "SubnetId": {"Ref":"Subnet"},
        "PrivateIpAddress": "10.0.0.17", "AssociatePublicIpAddress": "false"}
        ]
      },
      "DependsOn" : "AttachGateway"
    },

    "IngressRule":{
      "Type":"AWS::EC2::SecurityGroupIngress",
      "Properties":{
        "GroupId":{ "Ref":"SecurityGroup" },
        "FromPort":"80",
        "ToPort":"80",
        "IpProtocol":"tcp",
        "CidrIp":"0.0.0.0/0"
      }
    }
  }
}
{code}
Change a value in the network interface section, but make sure to change the address, otherwise there will be a conflict.  A replacement resource will be required.

To test SecurityGroupIds 

{code}
{
  "Parameters" : {
    "ImageId" : {"Type" : "String"}
  },
  "Resources" : {
    "Instance" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Instance",
      "Properties" : {
        "ImageId" : {"Ref":"ImageId"},
        "SecurityGroupIds" : [{"Fn::GetAtt" : ["SG1", "GroupId"]}, {"Fn::GetAtt" : ["SG2", "GroupId"]}],
        "SubnetId" : {"Ref":"Subnet"}
      }
    },
    "SG1" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup",
      "Properties" : {
        "GroupDescription" : "SG1",
        "VpcId" : {"Ref":"VPC"}
      }
    },
    "SG2" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup",
      "Properties" : {
        "GroupDescription" : "SG2",
        "VpcId" : {"Ref":"VPC"}
      }
    },
    "Subnet" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Subnet",
      "Properties" : {
        "CidrBlock" : "10.0.0.0/24",
        "VpcId" : {"Ref":"VPC"}
      }
    },
    "VPC" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::VPC",
      "Properties" : {
        "CidrBlock" : "10.0.0.0/16"
      }
    }
  }
}
{code}

start with the above template, and change the value of SecurityGroupIds.  If you are in a VPC, it should change with no-interruption.

If you use those fields in a non-vpc it will require replacement.

To test SecurityGroups 

{code}
{
  "Parameters" : {
    "ImageId" : {"Type" : "String"}
  },
  "Resources" : {
    "Instance" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Instance",
      "Properties" : {
        "ImageId" : {"Ref":"ImageId"},
        "SecurityGroup" : [{"Ref" : "SG1"}, {"Ref" : "SG2"}]
      }
    },
    "SG1" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup",
      "Properties" : {
        "GroupDescription" : "SG1"
      }
    },
    "SG2" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup",
      "Properties" : {
        "GroupDescription" : "SG2"
      }
    }
  }
}
{code}

start with the above template in a non-vpc setup, and change the value of SecurityGroups.  It will require replacement.

To test SubnetId, try
{code}
{
  "Resources" : {
    "Instance" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Instance",
      "Properties" : {
        "ImageId" : "emi-3b3f6aae",
        "SubnetId" : {"Ref" : "Subnet2"}
      }
    },
    "Subnet1" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Subnet",
      "Properties" : {
        "CidrBlock" : "10.0.1.0/24",
        "VpcId" : {"Ref" : "VPC"}
      }
    },
    "Subnet2" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Subnet",
      "Properties" : {
        "CidrBlock" : "10.0.0.0/24",
        "VpcId" : {"Ref" : "VPC"}
      }
    },
    "VPC" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::VPC",
      "Properties" : {
        "CidrBlock" : "10.0.0.0/16"
      }
    }
  }
}
{code}
Update the stack and point to the other subnet.  Will require replacement.

For Volumes, try the template:
{code}
{
  "Resources" : {
    "Instance" : {
      "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Instance",
      "Properties" : {
        "ImageId" : "emi-c66043f5",
        "Volumes" : [
          {"Device": "/dev/vdc" , "VolumeId" : {"Ref" : "Vol1"}},
          {"Device": "/dev/vdd" , "VolumeId" : {"Ref" : "Vol2"}},
          {"Device": "/dev/vde" , "VolumeId" : {"Ref" : "Vol3"}}
        ]
      }
    },
    "Vol1" : { "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Volume", "Properties" : {"AvailabilityZone" : "one", "Size" : "2"}},
    "Vol2" : { "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Volume", "Properties" : {"AvailabilityZone" : "one", "Size" : "2"}},
    "Vol3" : { "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Volume", "Properties" : {"AvailabilityZone" : "one", "Size" : "2"}},
    "Vol4" : { "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Volume", "Properties" : {"AvailabilityZone" : "one", "Size" : "2"}},
    "Vol5" : { "Type" : "AWS::EC2::Volume", "Properties" : {"AvailabilityZone" : "one", "Size" : "2"}}
  }
}
{code}
And change values of devices and volumes in "Volumes" to update stack.  Some volumes may attach or detach but the instance should update with no interruption.
